result.execSummary:
The defendant Aaron D Quincy was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Adjudged Delinquent Possess Firearm, a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.29(2)(b).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Original Transcript (10 pages) commencing 09/08/2014 SENTENCING HEARING received and filed.

Attorney Chris Bailey in court, defendant Aaron D Quincy not in court, in custody.  Laura A. Crivello for Marissa Santiago appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Restitution hearing held. For the reasons placed on the record by the State, the Court orders restitution set at $0.

Defendant Aaron D Quincy in court with attorney Chris Bailey.  Paul M. Hauer for Hanna Kolberg appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Case scheduled for Restitution Hearing. State informs the Defense and Court that the victim was not notified. Court adjourns case for Restitution Hearing on 11-10-2014 at 8:30 a.m., Br. 17.
  Restitution hearing scheduled for November 10, 2014 at 08:30 am.

Defendant Aaron D Quincy in court with attorney Chris Bailey.  Defendant Aaron D Quincy in custody.  Patricia I. Daugherty for Marissa Santiago appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.  Additional statements by: Alex E. 
AS TO COUNT 1: 
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 4 YEARS, consecutive to any other sentence, with credit for 240 days time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 2 YEARS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 2 YEARS.  
Court costs, fees, assessments and surcharges, including the DNA surcharge to paid through collection by the department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b). Any remaining balance upon release to extended supervision shall be due immediately; failure to pay will result in an entry of civil judgment. 
Defendant is NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program or the Substance Abuse Program. 
CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
- Maintain Absolute Sobriety, no alcohol.
- No use or possession of controlled substances without a valid 
  prescription taken in the manner and fashion as prescribed.
- Defendant to participate in Alcohol and Drug Assessment
  and successfully complete recommended treatment
  including drug and alcohol testing. 
- No possession of any illegal drugs or controlled substances without a valid prescription. 
- No possession of any drug paraphernalia for use, distribution or manufacturing. 
- No possession of any firearms or weapons; fire ammunition. 
- Obtain/Maintain Full Time employment/school or a combination of both. 
- Defendant to complete Parenting class. 
- Defendant to complete Cognitive Intervention Program. 
- Defendant to have curfew from 10:00 p.m. to 6:00 a.m. unless for approved work or school activities. 
- Provide DNA sample, if not already done. 
- Court prohibits contact with Richard M., Maria P., and Geraldo R., during confinement and during Extended Supervision. 


Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting.
Court advises the Defendant that under Wisconsin Statute 302.113 the amount actually served may be extended, and that the Defendant could serve the entire bifurcated sentence in prison. The Defendant will be subject to certain conditions while on release to extended supervision, and a violation of any of those conditions may result in the Defendant being returned to prison.
